Cloud Infrastructure and Monitoring Setup

Overview
We setup a cloud environment on AWS to deploy and monitor honeypots. 
The goal was to create a system where we can run honeypots on an EC2 instance, collect logs, detect suspicios activity, and get alerts. 
We used EC2 for hosting, Docker to run containers, Cloudwatch for logging, SNS for alerts, and S3 to store logs securely. 

Architecture
The system is built around an EC2 instance where the honeypots will run using Docker.
Any activity on the system generates logs, which are collected by the Cloudwatch agent. 
These logs are then analyzed using metric filters. 
If something suspicious is detected like an error or failed attempt, a Cloudwatch alarm is triggered and sends an email alert through SNS.
All logs are also stored in an S3 bucket for backup and further analysis. 

EC2 → Docker Honeypot → Logs → CloudWatch → Alarm → SNS → Email
                                   ↓
                                   S3

Implementation Steps 

EC2 Setup
Created EC2 instance (Amazon Linux 2023).
Configured security groups (ports 80, 443, 8080).
Attached IAM role for SSM and CloudWatch.

Docker Setup
Installed Docker
Configured user permissions.
Tested deployment using Nginx container.

Logging (CloudWatch)
Installed CloudWatch agents.
Configured log collection from /var/log/messages.
Verified logs appear in CloudWatch.

Alerts (SNS + Alarm)
Created SNs topic and subscriptions.
Configured CloudWatch metric filter.
Created alarm to trigger notifications.

Storage (S3)
Created secure S3 bucket.
Enabled encryption (SSE-S3).
Enabled versioning for log retention.

Security Measures
Security was implemented using IAM roles for least privilege access, enecrypted storage in S3.
Restricted security group rules, and private log monitoring through CloudWatch.

Testing and Validation
The system was tested by deploying a Docker container and generating log events.
These logs were successfully captured in CloudWatch, and alerts were triggered via SNS when predefined conditions were met. 

Conclusion
The cloud setup successfully provides a secure, scalable, and monitored environemnet for deploying honeypots. 
It ensures real-time detection and alerting of suspicious activity while maintaining secure log storage. 


